fullIncidentDataDTO Data Type

Class to represent data sent for the creation of events (POST /rest/incidents).

Namespace
(Default)
Properties
name data type type namespace min/max occurs description
actions actionInfoDTO element 0/unbounded The list of actions available to the caller for execution.
artifacts incidentArtifactDTO element 0/unbounded Gets the list of artifacts for the incident. This data is accepted on a POST but not currently on PUT, but it should be in the future.
cm incidentCountsDTO element 0/1 The incidentCountsDTO for the incident. This contains information about the counts of records that were lost for the different geographical regions.
comments commentDTO element 0/unbounded Set some notes for the incident. This data is accepted on a POST but not currently on PUT, but it should be in the future.
dtm (custom) element 0/1 The incidentDataTypesDTO for the incident. This contains information about the types of data that were lost (e.g First Name, Last Name, Credit card number, etc.).
hipaa HIPAARiskDTO element 0/1 The HIPAARiskDTO for the incident. This contains information required by HIPAA. If HIPAA does not apply to this incident then the hipaa propert can be empty.
regulators regulatorsDTO element 0/1 The regulatorsDTO for the incident. This contains information about the regulators that are in effect for the incident. Note that the ids property of the regulatorsDTO contains non-state/province regulators. So for example, you'd include the ID of the "GLB Act" regulator here. State regulators will be used if record counts are specified for that state.
tasks taskDTO element 0/unbounded Gets the list of tasks for the incident. This data is not accepted on a POST or PUT. It is only used if want_full_data=true is specified when the incident is created. See also taskDTO.
Properties inherited from incidentDTO
string element 0/1 The address where the incident occurred (e.g. 125 Main Street).
string element 0/1 An XML text string describing the high-level assessment of the incident.

This is a readonly property.
string element 0/1 The city where the incident occurred.
boolean element 1/1 Is the incident confirmed? Specify true if you're sure this is an incident. Specify false if you're not yet sure. As an example, consider the case where a SIEM system reports suspicious activity that you want to investigate. The automatic entry of the incident would set confirmed = false. Once a human investigates and determines that an incident actually occurred, the user would set this field to true through the Co3 UI.
objectHandle element 0/1 The country where the incident occurred. This is a geo ID. See constDTO (geos property) for the possible values.
justUserDTO element 0/1 A justUserDTO object that represents the creator. This object will include the creator's email address, first name, last name, etc.
objectHandle element 0/1 The ID of the user that created the incident. This is a read-only property.
objectHandle element 0/1 The ID of the crime status. See also constDTO (crime_statuses property).
boolean element 0/1 Has data been compromised because of the incident? Specify true to indicate that data was definitely compromised. Specify false to indicate that data was definitely not compromised. Specify a null value to indicate that you do not yet know if data was compromised (a task will be created to get you to investigate.)
boolean element 0/1 Was an employee involved? true means that an employee was known to be involved. false means that an employee was definitely not involved. A null value means that it is unknown whether an employee was involved.

This value generally only applies if the "exposure type" is "individual". That is, if the incident was caused by an individual person.
dateTime element 0/1 The date the incident was closed. This is a read-only property.
int element 0/1 The total amount of money (in US dollars) that you could be fined if you ignore this incident. This is calculated by the Co3 rules engine based on the information that you provided.

This is a readonly property.
objectHandle element 0/1 The department within the company that the incident was related to.

This value generally only applies if the "exposure type" is "individual". That is, if the incident was caused by an individual person.
string element 0/1 The free-form text name of the individual who caused the incident. For example, if Mary Jones lost her laptop then you would set the exposure_individual_name to "Mary Jones".

This value generally only applies if the "exposure type" is "individual". That is, if the incident was caused by an individual person.
objectHandle element 0/1 The exposure type for the incident. This is used to track the origin of the exposure. For example, was the origin of the incident an "individual" or "external party".
objectHandle element 0/1 The vendor who caused the incident.

This value generally only applies if the "exposure type" is "external party". That is, if the incident was caused by an external party.
objectHandle element 0/unbounded The IDs of the incident types. An incident type is something like Malware, Phishing, etc.

The list of possible incident types and their ID values can be retrieved using the OrgREST resource (perform a GET on the /rest/orgs/{orgId} endpoint), which will return a fullOrgDTO object. This object has an "incident_types" property that will contain the valid values.
boolean element 0/1 true if the incident is to be run as a what-if scenario. In this case the incident is not saved to the database, but it's assessment property is set and (if want_full_data was requested) the fullIncidentDataDTO (tasks property) is set.

Setting this value to false will cause an incident to be created.
string element 0/1 If this incident was a crime then this property indicates where it was a crime.
int element 0/1  
objectHandle element 0/unbounded The list of member user IDs.

The list of users is available in the fullOrgDTO (users property).
boolean element 0/1 Is a negative "public relations" (PR) response likely because of this incident? true indicates that a negative PR response is likely. false indicates that a negative PR response is unlikely. A null value means that you do not know if a negative PR value is likely or unlikely.
objectHandle element 0/unbounded A list of IDs of all of the NIST attack vectors that apply.

These values come from NIST 800-61 (see http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-61rev2/SP800-61rev2.pdf).

Note that the IDs specified here are internal Co3 IDs. The list of IDs is available in the constDTO (nist_attack_vectors property).
int element 0/1 The ID of the organization where the incident resides.

This is a readonly property.
incidentPermsDTO element 0/1 Indicates that the current user's permissions are to various elements of the incident. For example, is the current user allowed to change the membership of the incident (stored in the change_members property of the returned object).
incidentPIIDTO element 0/1 The incidentPIIDTO for the incident. This contains information about privacy breaches.
(custom) element 0/1 The custom properties (fields) for this incident. Use this to set/get custom properties for the incident. For example, if you have a custom field called moon_phase then you would set/get it's value using incident.properties.moon_phase.
string element 0/1 Free form text field indicating who reported the incident.
objectHandle element 0/1  
textContentDTO element 0/1  
dateTime element 0/1 The date the incident occurred.
objectHandle element 0/1 The state where the incident occurred. This is a geo ID. See constDTO (states property) for the possible values.
taskChangeDTO element 0/1 Gets information about what tasks were added or removed by the previous PUT operation. This only applies for PUT operations where the incident has changed causing an automatic change to one or more tasks.

This is a readonly property.
int element 0/1 The version of the incident. Note that if you attempt to save an incident and the vers field doesn't match the current version, you will get a 409 "conflict" HTTP error code. This is done so you don't overwrite another user's changes.
string element 0/1 The ZIP/postal code where the incident occurred.
Properties inherited from partialIncidentDTO
dateTime element 0/1 The date the incident was created.
textContentDTO element 0/1 The description of the incident.
dateTime element 0/1 The date the incident was discovered. This is a required field and has significant implications for privacy-related incidents. Many of the tasks that get generated will have their due dates set based on this date.
dateTime element 0/1 The earliest due date of any incident task.
int element 0/1 The incident ID.
boolean element 0/1 true if this is a training incident (aka simulation). false indicates that it is a normal incident.
string element 0/1 The name of the incident.
objectHandle element 0/1 The ID of the incident owner.

The list of all available users is in the fullOrgDTO (users property).
objectHandle element 0/1 The ID of phase the incident is currently in (e.g. Engage, Detect/Analyze, Respond, Post-Incident).

The possible values are available in the fullOrgDTO (phases property).
string element 0/1 The incident status.

The possible values with their names are available in constDTO (incident_statuses property).
objectHandle element 0/1 The incident's severity.
